{
  "local_port": 33130,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I cook manchurian?",
  "response": "Cooking Manchurian is a delicious and popular Indo-Chinese dish that can be enjoyed as a snack or main course. Here are the steps to prepare Vegetable Manchurian, a common variant:\n\n### Ingredients:\n\n#### For the Manchurian Balls:\n- 2 cups grated cabbage\n- 1 cup grated carrot\n- 1/2 cup finely chopped capsicum (bell pepper)\n- 1/2 cup finely chopped beans (optional)\n- 1/4 cup finely chopped spring onions\n- 2 tablespoons all-purpose flour (maida)\n- 2 tablespoons cornflour (cornstarch)\n- 1 teaspoon ginger-garlic paste\n- Salt to taste\n- Black pepper to taste\n- Oil for frying\n\n#### For the Sauce:\n- 1 tablespoon oil\n- 1 tablespoon finely chopped garlic\n- 1 tablespoon finely chopped ginger\n- 2 green chilies, finely chopped\n- 1/4 cup chopped spring onion whites\n- 1/2 cup chopped capsicum (bell pepper)\n- 1/4 cup chopped carrot\n- 2 tablespoons soy sauce\n- 1 tablespoon chili sauce\n- 1 tablespoon tomato ketchup\n- 1 teaspoon vinegar\n- 1 tablespoon cornflour mixed with 3-4 tablespoons water (for thickening)\n- Salt to taste\n- Water as required\n- Spring onion greens for garnish\n\n### Instructions:\n\n#### Preparation:\n1. **Mixing and Shaping the Manchurian Balls**\n   - In a large mixing bowl, add the grated cabbage, carrot, capsicum, beans (if using), and spring onions.\n   - Add ginger-garlic paste, all-purpose flour, cornflour, salt, and pepper.\n   - Mix everything well. The moisture from the vegetables should help bind the mixture. If it\u2019s too dry, you can add a little water, and if too wet, you can add a little more flour or cornflour.\n   - Shape the mixture into small balls of about 1.5 to 2 inches in diameter.\n\n2. **Frying the Manchurian Balls**\n   - Heat oil in a pan for deep or shallow frying.\n   - Once the oil is hot, add the vegetable balls carefully. Fry them until they turn golden brown and crispy.\n   - Remove the fried balls and set them aside on a paper towel to drain the excess oil.\n\n#### Preparing the Sauce:\n3. **Saut\u00e9ing the Aromatics and Vegetables**\n   - Heat 1 tablespoon oil in a wok or large frying pan.\n   - Add the chopped garlic, ginger, and green chilies. Saut\u00e9 for a few seconds until fragrant.\n   - Add the spring onion whites, capsicum, and carrot. Stir-fry for 2-3 minutes.\n\n4. **Making the Sauce**\n   - Add soy sauce, chili sauce, tomato ketchup, and vinegar to the pan.\n   - Stir well to combine, then pour in about 1 to 1.5 cups of water, depending on how much sauce you want.\n   - Bring the mixture to a boil.\n\n5. **Thickening the Sauce**\n   - Add the cornflour mixture (cornflour mixed with water) to the sauce.\n   - Stir continuously until the sauce thickens.\n\n6. **Combining Everything**\n   - Once the sauce has thickened, add the fried Manchurian balls.\n   - Stir well to coat the balls evenly with the sauce.\n  \n#### Final Touches:\n7. **Garnishing**\n   - Garnish with chopped spring onion greens.\n\n### Serving:\nServe the Vegetable Manchurian hot. It can be enjoyed as is, or with fried rice, noodles, or plain rice.\n\n### Tips:\n- Adjust the consistency of the sauce by adding more water if needed.\n- You can add other vegetables as per your preference.\n- For a healthier version, you can bake the Manchurian balls instead of frying them.\n\nEnjoy your delicious homemade Vegetable Manchurian!",
